'''Daniel Dickey''' is a published writer, photographer,<ref>http://www.fau.edu/coastlines/Authors.php</ref> and educator. His classroom has been featured nationally in radio reports on [[NPR]] and locally on WLRN and State Impact Florida.<ref>http://wlrn.org/post/make-high-schoolers-want-read-miami-teacher-makes-it-competition</ref><ref>https://stateimpact.npr.org/florida/2014/11/12/ballin-on-a-budget-how-a-miami-teacher-keeps-his-library-stocked/</ref> As a writer, Dickey's opinion editorials have been published in several top 50 newspapers—most notably, political commentary in the [[Sun Sentinel]] and [[Hartford Courant]].<ref>http://www.courant.com/topic/entertainment/music/sfl-daniel-dickey-middle-classes-must-cut-through-dogma-spin-20120130,0,7778470.story.</ref><ref>http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/opinion/purple/sfl-daniel-dickey-middle-classes-must-cut-through-dogma-spin-20120130,0,7486853.story</ref> Furthermore, Dickey’s op-ed championing the importance of [[education]] was used to lobby the Florida Senate against statewide budget cuts and his 2012 letter to the editor of the [[Gainesville Sun]] stressed our country's need for equal rights.<ref>http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-02-24/news/fl-letters-0224-20120224_1_religious-freedom-jewish-women-college-budget-cuts</ref><ref>http://www.gainesville.com/article/20120703/OPINION02/120709974?p=3&tc=pg</ref> In December 2013, Dickey wrote a humor-based piece challenging consumerism that quickly went viral with over 6,500 social shares in a 24-hour period.<ref>http://elitedaily.com/life/youre-quarter-life-crisis-arent-alone/</ref> Also active in the satirical arts, a one-act play penned by Dickey, ''Don't Forget to Floss'', was produced and recently premiered in [[New York City|New York]]'s West Village.<ref>{{cite web|title=Third Annual Shortened Attention Span Fest Hosts 22 Original Short Plays 6/4-28 |url=http://broadwayworld.com/article./Third_Annual_Shortened_Attention_Span_Fest_Hosts_22_Original_Short_Plays_6428_20090601 |date=June 1, 2009 |accessdate=December 3, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
Focused on the intersection between education and policy, Dickey announced his candidacy for a City Commission seat in [[Weston, Florida]] during the November 2012 elections.<ref>http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-06-08/news/fl-cities-election-qualifying-20120608_1_scott-yardley-commission-seats-lesa-le-peerman</ref> Local media highlighted that despite losing the election, Dickey, a college student at the time, gained 42% of the vote while spending under $425.00. His opponent, an incumbent, and son-in-law to a prominent Florida politician,<ref>http://www.browardbeat.com/gambling-and-big-sugars-school-board-candidate-franklin-sands/</ref> spent over $24,000.
After the election, Dickey focused fully on urban education and joined [[Teach For America]] as a [[writing]] and [[debate]] teacher in an inner city high school.<ref>https://twitter.com/TeachForAmerica/status/529034733754515456</ref> During his first two years in the classroom, he was recognized by [[DonorsChoose.org]] for raising over $105,000 for 75 teachers in low-income schools<ref>http://www.donorschoose.org/blog/2013/11/19/what-do-fairy-dust-and-75-new-donorschoose-org-teachers-have-in-common/</ref> and praised publicly by [[American Federation of Teachers]]' President, [[Randi Weingarten]], for his persistent energy and enthusiasm as an educator.<ref>https://twitter.com/rweingarten/status/529392038908022784</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/rweingarten/status/529391666546081793</ref> Additionally, Dickey not only endorsed [[Teach For America]]’s Million Word Campaign, but more so—turned it into a competitive classroom and school-wide initiative featured in a report on [[National Public Radio]].<ref>https://www.facebook.com/NPR/posts/10152984782096756</ref> Notably, Dickey has also participated in recruitment events to encourage college students to consider education and public service as long-term career paths.<ref>https://crowdhall.com/h/356/</ref>
Acting as an ambassador in the [[Chevron Corporation]]’s Fuel Your School campaign,<ref>http://www.fuelyourschool.com/</ref> Dickey volunteered to help teachers in [[Title I]] schools apply for and receive educational funding for their classrooms. This initiative led to more than $500,000 being distributed to teachers in high-need schools; consequently, Dickey was recognized for his service by the [[Miami Marlins]] and asked to throw out the first pitch at their season opening game.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7epMbx528y0&feature=youtu.be</ref>
